<HEADLINE>
<P>
'PARENTAL NOTIFICATION' LAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Once again, the U.S. Supreme Court, in its finite wisdom, has dealt women yet 
another blow to their reproductive freedom via its upholding of Ohio's and 
Minnesota's "Parental Notification" laws. 
</P>
<P>
Please understand me. 
</P>
<P>
I am completely in favor of having both parents and teen-agers involved when a 
crisis pregnancy occurs. But for the highest court in the land to mandate the 
"Ozzie and Harriet Syndrome" on today's teen-age women is very sad. To be faced 
with an unwanted pregnancy is enough of an emotional trauma, but to add to that 
having to, by law, tell a parent who may or may not be understanding or 
supportive, or worse yet, to have to go before a judge on what amounts to a 
very personal issue is unthinkable! 
</P>
<P>
The day after the decision was handed down, the National Right to Life 
Committee was quoted as calling it "a major victory for both parents and unborn 
children." Too bad they can't ask young Spring Adams, who lived in one of the 
"notification" states, how she feels about this law. After being raped by her 
father, a single parent, she became pregnant. When she went to him to get 
permission (by law) to terminate the pregnancy, he promptly shot her dead. 
</P>
<P>
I predict two things will result from this decision: More babies will be having 
babies, and more young women will be dying from self-induced or clandestine 
abortions. I'm sure the Right to Life Committee is pleased. 
</P>
<P>
CHRISTOPHER B. CRINER 
</P>
<P>
Tustin 
</P>
</TEXT>
