<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUTH DRAMA WORKSHOP IS IN JEOPARDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID COLKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The continuation of the Teen-Age Drama Workshop, now in its 34th summer season 
at Cal State Northridge, has been placed in question by the new year-round 
school policy. 
</P>
<P>
The workshop -- which counts among its alumni performance artist Bill Irwin, 
Tony Award-winning actor Michael Rupert and actress Mare Winningham -- is an 
intensive eight-week program that gives students the chance to work on several 
productions. 
</P>
<P>
But next year, with traditional summer vacation greatly shortened for many 
teen-agers at San Fernando Valley schools, the program may come to an end. 
</P>
<P>
"There has been talk about quitting, but the major emphasis has been on trying 
to fit in with the new schedule," said William Schlosser, who originated the 
program in 1956 and although retired still acts an adviser to the 160-student 
workshop. 
</P>
<P>
"We may have to cut back the number of students we now take," he said. 
</P>
<P>
CSUN officials said no decision has been made on the fate of the workshop. 
DAVID COLKER 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071390-0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 246724 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 13, 1990, Friday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
