<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: WARNING LIGHT CAUSES FORCED LANDING AT LAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A United Airlines DC-10 bound for Washington with 268 passengers aboard was 
forced to return to Los Angeles International Airport Thursday when a fire 
warning light activated shortly after takeoff. The plane, operating on two of 
its three engines, landed safely after dumping fuel and no injuries were 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
Dick Morrison, assistant air traffic manager, said the landing was "fairly 
normal" once the pilot noticed the light, which warns of an engine fire. The 
pilot shut off the engine and made a few passes over the ocean to dump fuel. 
</P>
<P>
Inspectors examined the aircraft, and determined that there was no fire and 
that the light was triggered by a malfunction, a United official said. No 
emergency evacuation procedures were necessary during the landing of United 
flight 54, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
