<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
SOVIETS CUT HUNGARIAN OIL 30% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUDAPEST 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hungary has been informed it will suffer a 30% reduction in Soviet crude oil 
deliveries and will have to look for other suppliers to fend off fuel 
shortages, a government spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Balazs Laszlo told a press conference a Hungarian negotiating party, 
which went to Moscow to try to persuade the Soviets to adhere to the current 
Soviet-Hungarian trade agreement, had been informed of the cuts Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
The negotiating team had gone to Moscow after Soviet Prime Minister Nikolai 
Ryzhkov announced a 7 million ton -- or 5% -- cut in Soviet oil exports 
overall. 
</P>
<P>
Laszlo said the Soviet cuts came in the wake of "the gradual depletion the 
established oil fields in the Soviet Union." He added, "The Soviet economy 
showed signs of a general collapse." 
</P>
</TEXT>
