<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
BART SIMPSON'S SMIRKING FACE SHOWS UP ON LSD-LACED STAMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ALBANY, N.Y. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bart Simpson, the television cartoon character whose image can be found on 
everything from coffee mugs to T-shirts, is turning up on stamps of the 
psychedelic drug LSD. 
</P>
<P>
Bart's smirking face has appeared on blotter acid, LSD-laced stamps that are 
sold in sheets, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Borcsok, 21, of Albany was charged Tuesday with possession of 261 
"hits" of hallucinogenic Bart Simpson stamps, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Another batch of the stamps surfaced last week in Pittsfield, Mass., about 40 
miles east of Albany, police there said. 
</P>
<P>
"These stamps are very obviously aimed at young children. Kids love Bart 
Simpson," said Steve Dnistrian, a spokesman for Phoenix House, a New York drug 
rehabilitation center. 
</P>
<P>
Cartoon characters such as Mickey Mouse and Goofy have been placed on blotter 
acid sheets since the 1960s, when the illegal drug became widely sold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Bart Simpson 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
